SIMPLE: poetry
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poetry
<hw>Po"et*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>poeterie</ets>. See <er>Poet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art
of apprehending and interpreting ideas by the faculty of imagination;
the art of idealizing in thought and in expression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For <qex>poetry</qex> is the blossom and the fragrance of all
human knowledge, human thoughts, human passions, emotions, language.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imaginative language or composition, whether
expressed rhythmically or in prose. Specifically: Metrical composition;
verse; rhyme; poems collectively; <as>as, heroic <ex>poetry</ex>;
dramatic <ex>poetry</ex>; lyric or Pindaric <ex>poetry</ex>.</as></def>
⟦ldquo⟧The planetlike music of <xex>poetry</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir P.
Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She taketh most delight⟦br⟧
In music, instruments, and <qex>poetry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poets' Corner</ent>⟦br⟧
